abstract = {The assay for transposase-accessible chromatin using sequencing ({ATAC}-seq) has become the preferred method for mapping chromatin accessibility due to its time and input material efficiency. However, it can be difficult to evaluate data quality and identify sources of technical bias across samples. Here, we present ataqv, a computational toolkit for efficiently measuring, visualizing, and comparing quality control ({QC}) results across samples and experiments. We use ataqv to analyze 2,009 public {ATAC}-seq datasets; their {QC} metrics display a 10-fold range. Tn5 dosage experiments and statistical modeling show that technical variation in the ratio of Tn5 transposase to nuclei and sequencing flowcell density induces systematic bias in {ATAC}-seq data by changing the enrichment of reads across functional genomic annotations including promoters, enhancers, and transcription-factor-bound regions, with the notable exception of {CTCF}. ataqv can be integrated into existing computational pipelines and is freely available at https://github.com/{ParkerLab}/ataqv/. Copyright \copyright 2020 The Authors. Published by Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.}
