abstract = {Transcriptome studies reveal pervasive transcription of complex genomes, such as those of mammals. Despite popular arguments for functionality of most, if not all, of these transcripts, genome-wide analysis of selective constraints indicates that most of the produced {RNA} are junk. However, junk is not garbage. On the contrary, junk transcripts provide the raw material for the evolution of diverse long non-coding (lnc) {RNAs} by non-adaptive mechanisms, such as constructive neutral evolution. The generation of many novel functional entities, such as {lncRNAs}, that fuels organismal complexity does not seem to be driven by strong positive selection. Rather, the weak selection regime that dominates the evolution of most multicellular eukaryotes provides ample material for functional innovation with relatively little adaptation involved. Copyright \copyright 2020 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.}
}
